  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 유묘(有苗) : '
    value: 《서경(書經)》 〈대우모(大禹謨)〉에, “유묘씨(有苗氏)가 왕정(王政)을 거역하므로 순(舜) 임금은 우(禹) 임금으로 하여금 가서 치게 하였으나 이기지 못하고 돌아오자, 순 임금은 크게 문덕(文德)을 베풀고 간우(干羽)로 하여금 대궐의 뜰에서 춤을 추게 하였더니, 그 후 70일 만에 유묘씨가 항복해 왔다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 갈(葛) …… 베풀매 : '
    value: 《서경(書經)》 〈중회지고(仲虺之誥)〉에, “갈(葛) 땅의 임금이 농민(農民)의 점심을 빼앗아 먹고 그 사람마저 죽이므로 탕(湯) 임금이 맨먼저 갈(葛)을 쳐부수자 그 땅 백성들의 말이, ‘우리 임을 기다린 지 오래였는데 임이 오셨으니 이제는 우리가 살았다.’ 했다” 한다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 지분(地分) : '
    value: 땅의 위치라는 말이다. 《원사(元史)》 〈하거지(河渠地)〉에, “창주(滄州)의 지분(地分)은 수면(水面)이 육지보다 높다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 학렬(鶴列) : '
    value: 진(陣) 이름이다. 《장자(莊子)》 〈서무귀(徐无鬼)〉에, “반드시 여초(麗譙)의 사이에 학렬(鶴列)을 치라는 법은 없을 것이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 옷소매를 떨치고[投袂] : '
    value: 옷 소매를 떨치며 분연히 일어선다는 말이다. 《좌전》선공(宣公) 14년조에, “옷소매를 떨치고 일어난다[投袂而起].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 관(冠)을 찌를 지경 : '
    value: 《사기(史記)》〈인상여전(藺相如傳)〉에, “성난 머리칼이 곧장 솟아 관을 찌른다[怒髮直上衝冠].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 근심을 나누게[分憂] : '
    value: 임금의 근심을 분담한다는 뜻으로, 한 지방을 맡아 다스리던 자에게 쓰는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 잠식(蠶食) : '
    value: 다른 사람의 물건을 침식하기를 마치 누에가 뽕잎을 갉아먹듯이 한다는 말이다 《사기(史記)》〈진시황기(秦始皇紀)〉에, “목공(穆公) 때부터 차츰 제후(諸侯)를 잠식(蠶食)하였다[自穆公以來稍蠶食諸侯].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 적미(赤眉)는 항복하고 : '
    value: 서한(西漢) 말기에 왕망(王莽)이 한(漢)나라를 빼앗을 적에, 낭아(狼玡) 사람 번숭(樊崇)이 거(莒) 땅에서 군사를 일으켰는데, 모두 눈썹을 붉게 물들여 왕망의 군사와 구별하게 하고, 강회(江淮) 지방에 횡행하여 그 형세가 자못 성하였는데, 뒤에 광무제(光武帝)에게 패하여 망하였다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 계옥(桂玉) : '
    value: 시량(柴糧)을 말한 것이다. 나무가 귀해서 계수나무와 같고, 쌀이 귀해서 옥과 같다는 말로 진귀하다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 행조(行朝) : '
    value: 행재(行在)와 같은 말로, 천자가 순행하여 머물러 있는 곳을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 호종(扈從) : '
    value: 천자의 거가(車駕)를 수행하는 사람을 이른다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 간식(旰食) : '
    value: 식사 때를 지나서 늦게 먹는다는 말이다. 《좌전(左傳)》소공(昭公) 20년에, “초(楚)나라 임금이나 대부(大夫)는 아마도 제 때에 밥을 먹지 못할 것이다[楚君大夫 其旰食乎].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 팔조(八詔) : '
    value: 조(詔)는 되놈의 말에 왕이라는 뜻이다 《당서(唐書)》 〈남만전(南蠻傳)〉에 나온다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 운몽(雲夢)에 노니는 : '
    value: 《사기》 〈한 고조기(漢高祖紀)〉에, “어떤 사람이 초왕(楚王)  한신(韓信)이 반역을 꾀한다고 고하므로, 고조(高祖)는 좌우에게 대책을 물었다. 좌우는 다투어 치자고 하였으나, 결국 진평(陳平)의 꾀를 받아들여 마침내 운몽(雲夢)에 노닌다고 거짓 하여, 제후(諸侯)를 진(陳)에 집합하게 하고서 초왕이 나오자 곧 사로잡았다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 동천(東遷) : '
    value: 주(周)나라 여왕(勵王)이 견융(犬戎)에게 망한 뒤에, 주 평왕(周平王)이 도읍을 호경(鎬京)에서 동쪽의 낙읍(洛邑)으로 옮긴 일.
  - key: '[주-D017] 남도(南渡) : '
    value: 진(晋)나라가 오호(五胡)의 침략을 못 견디어 원제(元帝)가 도읍을 강을 건너 남쪽의 건업(建業)에 옮겼다. 그래서 뒤에 동진(東晋)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 봉의(鳳扆) : '
    value: 의(扆)는 집 가운데 칸을 말한 것이다. 제좌(帝座)를 의좌(扆座)라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 등봉(登封) : '
    value: 천자(天子)가 순수(巡狩)하고 산에 올라 봉하는 예를 말한다. 한(漢)나라 무제(武帝)가 숭산(嵩山)에 올라 봉하였다.
english:
  title: The Jianghuai Memorial
  author: Choi Chiwon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly submits this memorial. Your servant reflects that when Sage Shun marched against the Youmiao, he cultivated virtue and ultimately received their submission. When Tang the Sage began his campaign at Ge, spreading benevolence, all people competed to return and found new life. These stand as fair tales of ancient and modern times, truly the glorious deeds of enlightened rulers. Therefore, your servant dares to bear the weight of careful responsibility and turns his sincerity toward the sun, humbly presenting the threads of advantage and harm, hoping to answer the aspirations of all civilized peoples and barbarian lands alike. Your servant proceeds without measuring his own blindness and foolishness, though he risks offending the sacred wisdom. Your servant is filled with utmost reverence and fear, bowing repeatedly.

    Your servant has heard that the sun and moon perfect themselves through their eternal motion across the heavens, and the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers fulfill their purpose by flowing toward the sea. When those above illuminate their nourishing warmth and those below complete the flow of their courses, it is nature's harmony. Yet heaven's disasters cannot be prevented by human strength alone, and those lands spared from warfare are few. Therefore, your servant ventures to present omens of eternal peace and words of possible restoration.

    Since bandits occupied the capital and military forces were conscripted from distant garrisons, the fierce and swift battalions initially followed the crane formations, yet soon returned in disorder. The stubborn rebels still cling to their ant-mounded strongholds, making complete annihilation difficult. How could your servant merely cast aside his robes and rise in protest? His very hair stood on end, ready to pierce his crown. Recently, leading the naval forces, he temporarily stationed them along the river's edge, determined to depart from the Chu shores in morning and reach the Han banks by evening, unfurling banners in the winds of Shang Ridge and drawing swords through the mists of Qin Plain. He hoped to launch a swift campaign and contribute what meager service he could. Subsequently, upon receiving the imperial edict, forces were recalled, for His Majesty graciously allowed him to share the burden of governance without abandoning his post. Your servant advances and retreats only by command, maintaining integrity from beginning to end. Rather than face reproach for neglecting duty, how could he presume to compete for merit?

    Moreover, should the Jianghuai region fall silent and military forces be hastily withdrawn, surely catastrophe will follow. The rich lands of the south will become mere sustenance for voracious invaders, while the powerful neighbors to the north will secretly extend their whale-like jaws. With military supply routes severed, provisions will inevitably run short. Therefore, having received the imperial command, forces have been recalled. Now the red-browed rebels submit on all sides, and the eight provinces enjoy the peace of their people. The imperial grace spreads everywhere, and strategic measures are roughly implemented. Yet with bandits still loose within the passes and the frontiers only precariously secure, this violates the principle of the ruler advancing first, and your servant is deeply ashamed.

    Your servant humbly contemplates that the emperor, in surveying the realm and extending righteousness, has encamped for considerable time. Though the Turtle Citadel stands magnificent and strong as golden walls and bronze moats, the expenses of the Fengxuan's royal journey concern us like precious jade. Furthermore, the western regions have long been renowned as prosperous, precisely because northern merchants benefit from the tea trade, thereby enriching military provisions. Yet now when each province sends memorials, they require half a year to return; when tribute is collected, it takes a full year to arrive. This is because the roads stretch far and wide, and warfare obstructs passage. Many suffer plunder, yet few reach the traveling court. The costs of hiring and wages deplete resources grievously. When goods are transported by water then by land, one stone requires one bushel to move it. Thus taxation breeds resistance, while soldiers remain underfed. Your servant fears that the entourage is vast and feasts are lavish. Though all resources of the three Shu regions are exhausted, they can scarcely supply the hundred offices. Should worries of delayed meals arise, the hope of officials cannot be satisfied.

    Furthermore, the Shu region lies distant in remote lands, bordering the barbarian realms. Great serpents conceal their venom, and bestial hearts are unpredictable. Should invaders seize the opportunity to breach the borders and lead their forces across the Lu River, though the six armies may display the prowess of bears and tigers to overwhelm enemies, the eight southern kingdoms' jackals and wolves wreak havoc unpredictably. Events must be anticipated before they occur; disasters must be prevented before they arise.

    Your servant humbly begs that Your Majesty examine this servant's loyalty and heed his candid words. Let the western journey be deferred, and instead undertake the southern tour. Let every place shed its resentment at being abandoned, and each person find peace in their devotion to the throne. How greatly would the realm rejoice! How greatly would the realm rejoice!

    Consider this: distant hunts at the Yellow River and false excursions to Cloud Dream were undertaken to advance kingly affairs yet bend to circumstances. How much more fitting, then, that the Jianghuai region—that prosperous land—and Wu and Chu—those flourishing domains—should receive the emperor who has governed nine years, making all four seas his household. This is not like the Zhou's eastern migration nor comparable to the Jin's southward crossing. The rebel's lair of vicious darkness has festered long; its foulness cannot easily be cleansed. Even if cities are recovered, the imperial chariot should not immediately return. Would not Yangdu and Yueyue, the Cassia Garden and renowned regions, see foreign envoys drawn easily to court, with the tributes of nine provinces never lacking a month?

    Your servant respectfully petitions that Your Majesty turn the Fengyi about and set forth upon the Dragon Boat. Then surely the mountain spirits will sweep clear the winds of the Three Gorges, and the river gods will calm the waves of Nine Rivers. Let the traces of Yu be sought afar, truly fulfilling the circuit of Yao. Once, the sun gleamed upon the Brocade River and heaven did not tilt toward the northwest. Now the wind sweeps the marshland realm, and earth lacks nothing in the southeast. Thereafter, send envoys to purify the palace, raise the standards of authority, display magnificent ceremony upon returning to the capital, and announce the glorious achievements at the great consecration.

    Though your servant's understanding of adaptation is dim, his resolve to aid the realm remains steadfast. He dares present this rough draft and humble perspective, overwhelmed by reverence for the sage and gratitude for imperial grace.
  footnotes:
    - The references to Shun's conquest of Youmiao and Tang's campaign at Ge are classical exemplars of virtuous rulership achieving submission through moral influence rather than force alone.
    - The 'crane formations' and 'ant-mounded strongholds' are military terminology suggesting organized military order contrasted with stubborn defensive positions.
    - The 'Turtle Citadel' (Gui Cheng) likely refers to Chang'an, the imperial capital.
    - The 'three Shu regions' refers to the prosperous Sichuan territories, a major source of imperial resources.
    - The 'Three Gorges' and 'Nine Rivers' are geographical features of the Yangtze River region, symbolizing the natural majesty of the southern tour route.
    - The 'great consecration' (dengfeng) refers to the classical imperial ritual of ascending sacred mountains to announce achievements to heaven.
